GitHub Desktop is a graphical tool that allows users to manage Git repositories easily without using command-line
commands. In Git, a commit is used to record changes made to one or more files in a branch. 

Each commit is assigned a unique identifier called a SHA (hash), which stores details such as what changes were made, when they
were made, and who made them.

GitHub Desktop continuously detects file changes and displays them in the “Changes” section. Users can decide
which files or specific lines should be included in a commit. This is done using staging, which helps in creating
meaningful and well-organized commits.
